Rudy,

Yes, I see your problem.  From A.CS.CMU.EDU you want to be able to type
"RUDY" and get RUDY.FAC.CS.CMU.EDU because it's the natural completion and
happens to be a unique name.  Of course if someone created a host named
RUDY.WARP.CS.CMU.EDU then you'd have a problem since they would be equally
"good" completions.

I'm glad we have much less of this at Stanford, where the decision has
been to avoid creating subdomains for the time being.  As long as the
namespace is of a manageable size, a single domain causes fewer headaches.
Just because an administrative hierarchy exists doesn't mean you have to
use it!

Something I definitely advocate is the ability for each user to define
"private" translations of nicknames into domain names (preferably fully
specified).  These would be applied before any of the domain-name lookup
mechanism gets to see the name.

						Joe

